tem from a weakened sense of collective racial identity? Simpson tackles the peculiar institution of black conservatism by interviewing college students to determine their political attitudes and the ways in which these are shaped. The result is a penetrating interrogation of the relations between political affiliation, racial identity, and class situation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and government. 0aConservatismzUnited States. 0aLiberalismzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civil Rights.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081478101240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814788912.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814788912423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814788912/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK